    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Characteristic and unmistakable species. Body very elongate and slender with long tubular snout and tapering tail, middle rays of the forked tail fin extended into a long, tapering filament. Eyes large. Swims horizontally in water column with body horizonal and linear. Colour uniformly green or brown with rows of blue dots dorsally.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_3876",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 120 cm total length, but specimens seen in this region smaller.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_3877",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread across the Indo-Pacific from South Africa up the east coast of Africa and right across to Mexico and South America, Australia and New Zealand. Recently also reported from Mediterranean, where it has rapidly spread and become abundant and is considered an invasive species that may threaten local fish species, after having migrated into the system through the Suez Canal.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Normally about Mossel Bay eastwards, only recently observed in False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_3878",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually seen singly or in small groups over shallow reefs or sea-grass beds (or here kelp beds). Mostly swims with a slow undulating movement, but when approaching prey advances stealthily and draws the body into an S shape, then lunges forward like a striking snake. May use other larger fish as cover when stalking prey.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_3879",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Feeds mostly on small fish, but also squid and shrimps.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_3880",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Sexual maturity is reached at a length of about 65 cm and the eggs are large, hatching into larvae that are about 6–7 cm at birth.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_3881",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Unmistakable and the only flutemouth in the region, although there are other rarer species in the eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_3882",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
